The binding affinity of copper to fully matched C1C2 is highest (6.5×106) while it is lowest (4.5×104) for the duplex containing clustered abasic site i.e. C1abC2ab (Fig. 6
                         and Table 3
                        ). Intermediate results were obtained for C1ab-C2 and C1-C2ab (Fig. S5 and Table S2). Thus the thermodynamic data is in great agreement with fluorescence, circular dichroism and thermal melting data andauthenticate that the duplex having clustered abasic site are inefficient for Cu NCs formation. This shows that presence of one or two abasic sites in a DNA strand of finite length contribute toward notable differences in the templating behaviour of the DNA that could be used to our advantage for their sensible detection.
